JOSEPH OZANNE: You can come
and see the races.

00:48:48.710 --> 00:48:51.230
They're going to be
races tomorrow.

00:48:51.230 --> 00:48:51.800
JULIAN GUTHRIE: Yeah
the racing--

00:48:51.800 --> 00:48:52.690
JOSEPH OZANNE: Two race.

00:48:52.690 --> 00:48:53.950
JULIAN GUTHRIE: Two-boat
racing starts tomorrow.

00:48:53.950 --> 00:48:59.130
So check it out.

00:48:59.130 --> 00:49:01.460
AUDIENCE: You mentioned earlier
that when you went to

00:49:01.460 --> 00:49:03.930
the fixed wing that there was
sort of a negotiation period

00:49:03.930 --> 00:49:07.340
with sailors because they're
not used to flying that.

00:49:07.340 --> 00:49:11.410
So what were the most
significant ways in which you

00:49:11.410 --> 00:49:16.030
had to overcome a sailor's
natural inclinations?

00:49:16.030 --> 00:49:18.540
Basically, what are the
significant differences

00:49:18.540 --> 00:49:21.500
between flying a standard
sail and a fixed-wing.

00:49:21.500 --> 00:49:23.050
JOSEPH OZANNE: It's still
a sailboat, so

00:49:23.050 --> 00:49:24.450
it's doing the same.

00:49:24.450 --> 00:49:25.870
So you try to propel
your boat.

00:49:25.870 --> 00:49:28.970
So it's just doing the same
thing, except the tool you're

00:49:28.970 --> 00:49:32.350
using to create the thrust
is different.

00:49:32.350 --> 00:49:36.490
So we just need to make sure
that the sailors understand

00:49:36.490 --> 00:49:41.010
that they still try to
create some thrust.

00:49:41.010 --> 00:49:47.040
And it's still like a normal
sail plan, except that the

00:49:47.040 --> 00:49:48.570
tool you're using
is different.

00:49:48.570 --> 00:49:51.810
So the way you create this
force is different.

00:49:51.810 --> 00:49:58.450
So the only thing is to teach
them what are the settings

00:49:58.450 --> 00:50:02.710
that will be OK to recreate
what was happening before.

00:50:02.710 --> 00:50:08.370
And then, so initially, it was a
bit complex for them because

00:50:08.370 --> 00:50:15.690
you rely more on numbers and
data and everything.

00:50:15.690 --> 00:50:21.570
Where, I mean, I remember during
the 2010 campaign where

00:50:21.570 --> 00:50:24.780
we had this one of the quote
that you're going to find in

00:50:24.780 --> 00:50:29.480
the book is normally a sailor
looks at his sail and checks

00:50:29.480 --> 00:50:32.250
how it fly, how it's
in the air.

00:50:32.250 --> 00:50:34.200
And when you go in an aircraft,
the pilot doesn't

00:50:34.200 --> 00:50:35.470
look at his wing.

00:50:35.470 --> 00:50:38.820
So it's just like, I just need
to get used to that.

00:50:38.820 --> 00:50:41.260
But overall, at the end, the
sailor will still use his

00:50:41.260 --> 00:50:44.030
feeling and how the
boat is loaded and

00:50:44.030 --> 00:50:45.310
how the boat reacts.

00:50:45.310 --> 00:50:47.240
So now they are the level where

00:50:47.240 --> 00:50:49.490
they can use it properly.

